x4freetext: Studsvik 6 MV Van de Graaff accelerator
equipped with a pulsing and klystron bunching
system. Delivers bursts of protons at a
repetition rate of 1 MHz with a pulse width at
half maximum of about 1.2 ns and average beam
current of 3 microAmps.
EN-RSL - The total energy spread due to straggling
of the protons in the entrance window, the amount of
tritium gas in the cell, and the finite geometry of the
target sample system has been estimated to be less
than +/- 30 keV.
Target cell of length 1.5 cm filled with tritium
gas to a pressure of 1.0 atm. The molybdenum entrance
window of the cell had a thickness of 4 mg/cm2.
The incident neutron energies were determined by using
a TOF difference between neutrons and gamma-rays from
the target over a known flight path.
Two identical 12.7 cm by 5.1 cm thick liquid
scintillators mounted on fast photomultiplier tubes
were used to measure the angular distributions of
elastically scattered neutrons. The detectors were
separated by an angle of 5 degrees in the azimuthal
plane and were positioned at a distance of 300 cm
from the scattering sample in a heavy shielding. The
total time resolution was 1 ns FWHM, the actual
angles were determined by means of a digitizer with
an angular resolution of less than 0.1 degr.
The neutron flux was determined using a TOF
neutron monitor consisting of a 5 cm by 5 cm fast
plastic scintillator coupled to a fast
photomultiplier tube.

x4freetext: - method of the
attenuation and multiple scattering in the polythene
samples correction
Optical model parameters.
Legendre coefficients determined.
.The background spectrum from the sample-in spectrum
was subtracted after the neutron flux normalization.
The different detector efficiencies were corrected
for. The angular distributions were corrected for
anisotropy of the neutrons from the H-3(p,n) reaction,
finite angular geometry, flux attenuation in the
scattering samples and multiple scattering. A
Monte Carlo program was used to treat the latter
three effects.
The attenuation and multiple scattering in the
polythene samples used for calibration were corrected
for by applying the parallel beam flux tables given
by Cranberg and Levin (see REL-REF) multiplied by
1.01 to correct for the divergence of the neutron beam
The time scale was calibrated absolutely by
means of a commercial time calibrator and the
uncertainty of the mean energies determined was
estimated to +-10keV.
Uncertainty in correction factor for
anisotropy < 0.5%
Uncertainty in correction factor for
flux attenuation 0.7%

Uncertainty in correction factor according
